BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:AI & Innovation Speaker Series - Zoë Hitzig
DTSTART;TZID=UTC;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260421T183000Z
DTEND;TZID=UTC;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260421T194500Z
UID:afba7d053ef8ff9ec5ea02108f407d0b@northwestern.edu
DESCRIPTION:Title: How People Use ChatGPT\nAbstract: Three years after its
  launch\, ChatGPT was used at least weekly by ten percent of the global ad
 ult population. This paper documents several important facts about how peo
 ple use ChatGPT using a large random sample of ChatGPT messages linked to 
 demographic data via an automated privacy-preserving process. ChatGPT usag
 e was initially higher among men and users from high-income countries\, bu
 t those gaps had closed substantially as of September 2025. Although non-w
 ork usage has grown relatively faster\, users on consumer plans still send
  hundreds of millions of work-related messages each day. Work-related Chat
 GPT usage is highly concentrated in knowledge-seeking activities like deci
 sion support and analyzing and interpreting information\, regardless of us
 er occupation. We develop a principal-agent model of AI chatbot usage that
  is motivated by evidence from people using ChatGPT both to ask for advice
  and to delegate tasks directly. The model highlights the central role of 
 users’ demand for customization due to idiosyncratic preferences\, which
  we call context. Using a novel classifier that measures conversational co
 ntext\, we find that users are more likely to ask AI chatbots for advice r
 ather than work output when their queries have higher context requirements
 . Since context must be transmitted by the user\, it may be a key bottlene
 ck to unlocking economic value from AI.\nBio: Zoë is currently with Anthr
 opic\, and a Junior Fellow at the Harvard Society of Fellows. She earned h
 er PhD in economics from Harvard University in 2023\, where she specialize
 d in research on privacy\, transparency\, and algorithms in markets and co
 mmunication. Zoë’s poetry\, known for its sharp intellect and imaginati
 ve breadth\, has appeared in prestigious publications such as The New York
 er\, London Review of Books\, and Boston Review. She is the author of two 
 acclaimed poetry collections\, including Mezzanine and Not Us Now\, which 
 explore themes at the intersection of philosophy\, economics\, and technol
 ogy.
LOCATION:Kellogg Global Hub\, 2211 Campus Drive\, Evanston\, IL
URL:https://ryaninstitute.kellogg.northwestern.edu/events/seminar-series-o
 n-ai-science-and-innovation-zo%C3%AB-hitzig
X-SOURCE:Northwestern University (Community)
END:VEVENT
